Classifaction model on Tips

  1. Project Statement : Predict if a particular taxi trip was able to secure a tip from the passenger for that ride
  2. Data set :
  1. Green Taxi data set for the Year 2019 and the Month of January from NYC government website.
  2. Taxi zone look up table , in order to get the borough where the taxi operated
  1. Contributor : Anirudh Suresh Ramchandran

drop_zones<-read.csv('data/drop_zones.csv')

Merging

Now since I was interested in also analyzing if the taxi getting a tip was depending on where it picked up the rider or dropped them, I merged them with two similar csvs. The first csv merged on the DOlocation and was able to give different boroughs from where the passenger was picked up by taxi driver.

# ---------------------------------------merge-----------------------------------------------------------

df<-left_join(df,pick_up_zones,by='PULocationID')

names(df)[names(df) == 'Borough'] <- 'pick_up_borough'
#names(df)
#drop locations 
df<-left_join(df,drop_zones,by='DOLocationID')

names(df)[names(df) == 'Borough'] <- 'drop_borough'

Feature engineering

Since we interested in predicting if a particular ride was able to secure a tip , we first calculate a variable tip_percenatge . Which is basically the ratio of the percentage tip amount by the total amount for that taxi ride . From this variable , we create another variable which indicates if a tip was received or not . Tips received are indicted using 1 while tips not received are indicated using 0. This variable gave_tip turns into our dependent variable

Exploratory data analysis For categorical Variables

In this section, for the EDA ,our main aim is understand how each independent variable influences the ride and the driver is able to hence secure a tip All the independent variables are compare with the dependent variable gave_tip. The variable gave_tip just explains if that particular trip (row in the data set) received a tip from the rider. Few variables such as RatecodeID were not studied owing to their skewness.

Inference :

This graph shows us the variation in tipping frequency based on picking up passengers in different boroughs. The different boroughs are Manhattan, Bronx, Queens, and Brooklyn. From the graph, we can infer that if a passenger is picked up from the Manhattan boroughs, they are most likely to tip than passengers picked up in other boroughs. This might be an important predictor variable.

From the heat map we can notice that tip_percentage is correlated to the improvement_surcharge, extra, tip_amount. It also looks like it is negatively correlated to the trip_distance. Now we will try and find the highly correlated variables to prevent multi-collinearity.

highlyCorrelated <- findCorrelation(correlationMatrix, cutoff=0.7)
# print indexes of highly correlated attributes
#print(highlyCorrelated)

# variables are 
names(cor_tibble[1])
## [1] "trip_distance"
names(cor_tibble[2])
## [1] "fare_amount"
names(cor_tibble[5])
## [1] "tip_amount"

So for our machine learning model we will not select all among these following variables : trip_distance,fare_amount,tip_amount . Since these variables are highly correlated among themselves and selecting them would lead to significant multicollinearity in our model

Train Test splits

#-----------------------------train /test sets-----------------------------------------

cols_include=c("passenger_count","trip_distance","tolls_amount","hour_p","avg_speed","payment_type","gave_tip","drop_borough")
#cols_include=c("passenger_count","trip_distance","improvement_surcharge","hour_p","avg_speed","gave_tip","drop_borough","pick_up_borough")
#cols_include=c("passenger_count","trip_distance","tolls_amount","hour_p","avg_speed","gave_tip","drop_borough")

#----------
x <- df[,(colnames(df) %in% cols_include)]
set.seed(105)
sample <- sample(1:nrow(df), 0.85*nrow(df)) 

train <-(x[sample,])
test <-(x[-sample,])

From our exploratory data analysis , we found that the number of passengers impacted the tips.If there was only one passenger they were found to tip more as compared to having more passengers.Furthermore the drop location seemed to impact whether that particular ride got tips or not. Picking up in Manhattan could result in a tip more than other locations We could have chosen either drop or the pick up borough(s), since both seemed to have some impact on the tips given. The speed also seemed to impact the tips hence it was also chosen as predictor variable. Furthermore the different pick up or drop hour were also looked like they affected the tips and even in this one of them could be chosen. In my case I choose the pick up hour as another predictor variable . Next taking the fare in the credit card seemed to get more tip as compared to accepting the payment in cash , hence that was also included . Lastly it was noted that having more tolls in the total fare of the ride seemed to impact the passengers giving that particular ride a tip

Random Forest Model

tip_rf <- rand_forest(trees=100, mode="classification") %>% 
  set_engine("randomForest") %>% 
  fit(gave_tip~., data= train)

Hyper parameter Tuning

# Create model with default parameters
control <- trainControl(method="repeatedcv", number=10, repeats=3)
train11=train1[1:1500,]

metric <- "Accuracy"
set.seed(7)
mtry <- sqrt(9)
tunegrid <- expand.grid(.mtry=mtry)
rf_default <- train(gave_tip~., data=train11, method="rf", 
                    metric=metric, tuneGrid=tunegrid, trControl=control)
print(rf_default)

#-----

control <- trainControl(method="repeatedcv", number=10, repeats=3)
train11=train1[1:15000,]

metric <- "Accuracy"
set.seed(7)
mtry <- sqrt(9)
tunegrid <- expand.grid(.mtry=mtry)
rf_random <- train(gave_tip~., data=train11, method="rf",
                    metric=metric, tuneLength=15, trControl=control)

print(rf_random)
plot(rf_random)

Owing to the lack of computational resources, I was not able to tune my model completely. I was only able to run the code to tune the mtry parameter of the random forest model. For the mtry parameter as well I was only able to feed in at the max 1500 rows for training in order to find the best parameter . Any more rows and the whole hyper parameter function was unable to converge

Results:

I was aiming to predict in which situations the taxi driver was able to secure a tip . Using parameters like car speed , its distance traveled , where the passenger was picked up and their location. Using these factors we were able to determine if a particular ride would be able to secure a tip or not with a success rate of around 88%. So in the end we can conclude that the taxi driver would be able to most tips if he / she followed the following steps :

  1. Picked up and dropped off a passenger in and around Manhattan
  2. Worked during the peak rush hours of 6-7 pm in the evenings
  3. Accepted payments in credits cards rather than cash
  4. Accepted rides within a 30 miles radius of their pickup locations While we cannot say these factors will always lead to the taxi ride getting tips , these factors might prove to help the taxi driver secure a tip from the passenger
